segments.text: This is February 22, 1985.
We are in the Crowne Plaza Hotel in Dallas, Texas.
This is Bob Cornish, and I'm interviewing Bob Wegner.
Bob, you've been in the Texas chapter and in Texas for many years.
Why don't you tell us about your beginning in Texas planning?
OK, in 1951, in the spring, the city of San Antonio held an election in which they had a referendum adopting the council manager form of government, as a consequence of which two things.
First, the city, then 36 square miles, a six mile square, became

much much larger as a result of going to the council manager form annexation took place on a large scale secondly the city was staff was reorganized and professionalized including the establishment for the first time of a department of planning both of these things led to my coming to san antonio and then ultimately to my leaving it two and a half years later in june of 52

Just after graduating from Harvard, I was hired by then-director William O. Parker to be the assistant director of slum clearance and urban redevelopment, which the city was undertaking per its charter provision as a new council manager city.

And it turned out, after about six months and a suit by some builders or developers or some similar group in San Antonio, that the charter provision was not sufficient authority for the city to get into slum clearance and urban redevelopment and take advantage of the federal legislation available for that purpose.
that state and Navy legislation was required.
And so the Office of Slum Clearance and Redevelopment was abolished.
Yes?
Bob, do you know who the planning director before Parker was?
According to my understanding, Bill Parker was the first planning director under the new council manager form.
And prior to that time, I'm just unaware.
I was led to believe that they did not even have a planning department prior to that time.
So Bill or Winston Martin would probably be able to tell you about that.

During the six months I was in the slum clearance redevelopment, as assistant director, I had the privilege, really, of hiring the first professional planner that I ever hired, who happened to be Wolfgang G. Rosler, who is now the head of the Department of Planning
Texas A&M Urban and Regional Planning.
And make that acting department.
Acting department, as much as he had somewhat, had been in the position for several years and then left it just to go back to teaching.
And now because of the reorganization going on there, he is stepping in temporarily to fill that position.
And he did some very fascinating things.
One of the things that he did while he was there that I remember was, and I worked with him on it, and then after he left it, he only stayed a very short time,
was to establish census tracts for the city of San Antonio.
That was the first accomplishment.

The 1950 census had been conducted there without census tracts, and he outlined a program for formalizing them or creating them, and then I followed through on the technical work needed to help achieve that by using aerial photographs and such and taking the block statistics and
prorating the counts and all that kind of thing, using some students from Trinity University in a sociology class there and a bunch of freedom calculators who actually make the conversion.
And so we gave them their first set of census tracts, which then stood them in good stead in 1960.
That was the real tangible accomplishment.
The second thing that I worked on in San Antonio was, after leaving, I went to the planning department then.
worked on drafting a revision of their zoning ordinance.
Unfortunately, my efforts, I think, were all for naught.

Because in the spring of 53, partly as a consequence of the first item that I mentioned at the beginning, the large annexation, there were a large number of disgruntled voters in San Antonio who were exploited by some of the
powers that were at the time, and they were so-called anti-manager forces, were elected to the council.
A man named White, who was associated with the White Hotel chain, was their leader, and he had been a council member previously.
Anyway, what happened was that they wanted to get rid of the manager, C.A.
Harrell, who at that time was the preeminent
manager in the country, having just left some 25 years as city manager in Cincinnati.
And CA Harrell very wisely had a contract that left them virtually no way to fire him, because there was no cause to fire him.
He had performed ably, and there was no complaint about his performance.
So they took what choice they did, and that was to reduce his salary to $1 a year, under which circumstances he was obliged to resign.
And shortly thereafter, they had a sequence of six city managers in six months, mainly department heads.
Then finally, they settled down.
But in the meantime, they cut the budget back very drastically.
And yours truly was, at each budget period, getting a little bit less and a little bit less.
So that by the time I left in the fall of 54, I was earning 20% less than I had started with.
back two and a half years earlier.
While in San Antonio, in addition to Bill Parker, the assistant director at the beginning was M. Winston Martin.

When the changeover came and Harrell left, Bill Parker was one of those department heads who resigned, and M. Winston Martin became the planning director and remained such for a long time, and it was largely due to his
support that I was even able to remain as an employee there at all, given the very tough budget situation that we had.
And I was forever grateful to him that he did give me that support.
Also on the staff at the time were two other gentlemen who achieved some prominence later in private practice in the firm of Mormon, Mock, and Green.
And these were Ed Mock and Bob Green.
Ed, I believe, was an architect by initial training.
And Bob Green was a landscape architect
The two of them eventually teamed up with a fellow named Mormon and had offices both in San Antonio and Houston and did some rather outstanding design work.
I think that they still are practicing.
The firm still exists.
The name has just recently been changed.
Ed Mock having died within the last two years, and Bob Green is probably in a semi-retired, if not a fully retired, state.
And I know is enjoying that very much.
Going down to Peru to view the comet in about a month or two.
Right now, maybe.
Anyways, the next association I had with Texas, I left there right around Thanksgiving or Halloween or something like that.
And my last day in the office, I recall, I taped a...
short program for the APA, or then the AIP, where I had been scheduled to give a talk about preparing the planning budget.
And I had to put it onto a dictaphone disk and send it on since I wasn't going to be able to attend the session.
And that was my last effort at the time to help support the progression in Texas.
Some other things I did while I was there that I just recall now was that I went around the state with some representatives of the state health department
one William Bell, who I believe was an attorney or a legal counsel for the health department, talking about and trying to promote the idea of urban redevelopment.

And some of the ideas that were coming to the fore at that time, some of the federal housing and home finance agency programs that cities could use, I went with Mr. Bell and went around the state talking on two or three or four occasions.

Later on, toward the end of the 50s, after some very successful work in Tulsa, which was a kind of a pioneering-type planning city, we got into a program which involved Fort Worth along with the metropolitan planning agencies in Tulsa and Little Rock and Wichita, Kansas, as well as the city and county of Denver planning agency.
This was a five-way...
demonstration project funded by, I think it was Housing and Home Finance Agency in the late 50s, to develop a computer, a data management system, really, using computer technology.
And we call it the Metropolitan Data Center Project.
It went on for some two to three years.
I started out as one of the conceivers of the project and came to Fort Worth on several occasions and visited with the staff there.
The director at that time, Mike Mahoney, may remember who it was because it was a guy who had a civil engineering background.

But the city of Fort Worth gave excellent support to the program, and they actually were one of the cities that really used some of the experience in data management that we developed in that program.
And one of the other byproducts was a system that eventually was adopted by HUD
as the format for land use systems, which was the concept of a parcel record, which had land use as one basic element, structure design as a second element, and then structure use as a third element.
How does this relate to the work of Al Gutenberg and his multiple land use classifications?
I think that either they were parallel
Or they were one led to the other.
And in terms of time, I don't know exactly the timing.
I do know that we did use the basic SIC code as the main one for coding of land use and for structure use as well.
So the exact history of that I'm not that well acquainted with.
But I know that we were either together or one came just before the other and one borrowed from the other.
HHFA never gave him any credit for his work.

Well, that's very unfortunate, because apparently, I know that one of our coworkers in Tulsa had been on the committee that name was in the booklet that came up with the harder HHFA land classification system, which was also endorsed by the highway.
Dot.
or whatever it was, the Highway Administration.
Well, it was the Bureau of Public Roads.
Bureau of Public Roads, yeah.
Federal Highway Administration.
And that was, his name was Donald, come to me later, Bond, but he'd also worked with Erling Helland for a while, and he went up to Kansas City and worked there.
In fact, he even became the director of planning in Kansas City, and then went into private practice.
The last thing I knew about him, he was working with some of the underground storage areas in the old abandoned mines right outside of Kansas City, or
some of us even in the city, Woodard.
His name is Don Woodard, W-O-O-D-A-R-D, and he was, his name is listed in that booklet, and he was on our staff when the data center was going on, that study was going on.
Then, what brought me to Texas was a study done by the Texas Research League in the mid-60s, about the time that some forces in Texas, including some in north central Texas very strongly, including
Tommy Vandegrift were pushing for in Arlington were pushing for state legislation to authorize multi-county planning agencies, councils of governments, and so forth.
Was Vandegrift mayor at that time?
He was mayor at that time, yes.
He was mayor for, as you probably recall, some 20 to 25 years, and that was right in the middle or part of the latter half of that time period.
Home years.
Yes.
And anyways,
Whatever groups, Mr. Vandegrift and others prevailed upon the legislature to see the wisdom of adopting a neighboring legislation for COGS or regional councils, if they're generically known.
And as part of the foundation of this, I believe, the Texas Research League entered into a study of metropolitan planning.
And as a part of which, they came to, or some of their team,
came to Tulsa and interviewed me as, at that time, the director of planning.
And I had taken over from Glenn Turner, who had succeeded Erling Helland, who was the first director, back in 53 when it was founded.
And then in 54 or 55, I believe, Turner came on.
And then in 63, I came on.

So sometime between 63 and the end of 66, essentially, probably in 65, people from the Texas Research League came in and interviewed me about how was the Tulsa Metropolitan Area Planning Commission working?
How did that function?
And they wanted to use it in their study of metropolitan planning for Texas.
And there are reports of that study available.
And they were, if not precedent or support for,
the legislation that enabled COGS to be established in Texas, they at least were part of that same movement of support.
The COGS in Texas were sort of a remake of the previous economic development districts, EDDs, that had existed before.
Pursuant to what, some National Resources Planning Board thing?
No, it was after that.
But these were then converted into COGS, likely.
Well, no, let me give you a bit more about that.
Another link that tied me with this, which you may be familiar with, because our paths first crossed back in the mid and late 50s when Tulsa was doing a central business district plan.
And you were a member of the consulting team of Noitre and Alexander that was doing the plan for the Tulsa Metropolitan Area Planning Commission.
At the same time, another member of that team was Harold F. Wise, who had his own consulting firm.
And one of the things that he eventually did was to prepare plans and work programs for state planning.
In fact, he became the single planner that prepared more state plans of that type than any other.
And among those that he was working on was Texas.
And so he was instrumental in his own limited way in having an influence upon the formation of the state planning regions in Texas, which then became the home base for each of the COGs.
And he did prepare also, after I came to Texas in January of 67, one year after the North Central Texas COG was established, he was the man that we hired to prepare our initial work program.
And he foresaw
a budget that none of us would believe at the time.
If we saw a budget of several million dollars, I believe it was two million dollars in a short period of time.

Well, the way it turned out was ultimately the budget of the North Central Texas COG went to ten million dollars, and it also turned out that the size of the staff increased for the first, let me see, probably, I'll say roughly ten years at the rate of one person a month on the average.
The staff was actually, in November of 66, when Bill Pitstick, who was still director, was hired, through, let's say, 10 years, there were 120 people on the staff 10 years later.
And Bill and Dan Petty, who was the second person to be hired, and I, who was the fourth, the third having been Bill's secretary, Linda Farr at that time, just couldn't believe that
Harold Franklin Wise was correct in his predictions about how far the budget would go.

As a matter of fact, he turned out to be conservative, all due, of course, to the availability of large amounts of federal aids for not only physical development planning and water planning and transportation planning, but also the various kinds of social and health-related planning and that kind of thing.
NCTCOG in the January of 67.
I came in as the director of regional planning and then did several other things, including being invited to be active in the AIP at that time.

From the outset of the short course back in around 1970, due to your, Bob Cornish, your initiative bringing the idea that you'd worked on in California to Texas with you, starting this short course, I was invited to take part in that from the very, and be on the task force from the very outset.
Frankly, I must admit, during the first year, my participation was in name
I was never able to get to any of the committee meetings, and there were three or four years and all that.
And it was only after that that I became active.
We paid all the expenses.
Well, be that as it may, maybe I didn't know that, whatever it was.
It was a very, very busy time at Cog, and it was very demanding work.
And at any rate, we initiated all kinds of new programs there.
I don't know how much of that history you want me to recount.
I should say this.
The Texas Association of Regional Councils has commissioned a history of regional councils in Texas, which I believe Jim Ray is preparing.
And this is supposed to be available at the end of this year, hopefully at the TARC annual conference in fall, which I believe will be in Galveston.
I'm not sure about them anyways.
That will be available to celebrate the 20th anniversary of the establishments of COGS in Texas.

And so rather than my trying to take time with that, I'll just skip that and ask you whether you want me to talk about the Educational Foundation and the short course perhaps as a little bit of something else that I was involved in.
Why don't you start first with the short course and how that got metamorphosed into the Educational Foundation.
The short course, and again, you were the fellow that promoted, initiated the idea here, based upon what you'd done in California.
And there is a paper that I think I provided you a copy with recently that I found in my file that you wrote about two years after.
I mean, it was late 60s, something like that.
And it recounts part of that history, and it was based upon, I think, the first short course that was held in San Antonio.
You actually told the story of that.
And the idea here was that this is a growing state, a state in which planning is growing.
The numbers of professional planners were rising.
The number of cities undertaking planning, appointing planning agencies, adopting zoning, et cetera, were increasing all the time.
And Texas, a state that now has some 1,000-plus cities and then had nearly that same number, and great demand for planning and for planning and zoning commissioners, and precious little background
very few professional planners on the job, and so there was a great need, a great demand evident to those of us in the profession for training of local officials.
We thought primarily of planning and zoning commissioners, but we also included the city council members and other elected officials.
So that came a little later.
Well, but the idea, but the name was added to the title after only about two or three years, really.
Initially it was a short course for planning commissioners,
And that, as I say, I've collected a little copy of the programs, and I don't have all of them, but they will be completed and become part of the Foundation archives.
And Mike McAnally is going to help get that all together.
And so I also refer you to the summary, which I have compiled, such as it is, with the names of the various coordinators who ran each of the short courses.
I really think that we ought to have the people on the task force as well as the coordinator.
Yeah, the task force names are going to be on there, too.
Yeah, because they're the ones that initially the idea was to provide policy.
And then the coordinators were to administer the policy.
So it's important to have those policy centers down there.
Well, as a matter of fact, you read my own mind when you said it.
Because what I did was I tried to make a very brief summary of the years from 1970 to 71 right
through 1985 with both the sites of the short course, the dates of the short course, the coordinator of the short course, and the size of the task.
All right, with the short course summary being inserted at this point, then I would suggest that we talk about the Educational Foundation.
And the impetus for starting on this was
somewhat vague in my mind, but maybe you can help recall.
Well, I think John Shanahan was the president at the time, and I was vice president in that chapter.
And John, having had substantial business experience and also with being a lobbyist, was concerned about the net proceeds that we were making every year, which amounted to a couple thousand dollars.
And the question of being tax exempt came up in terms of income tax.

And so after substantial investigation around Austin with non-taxable corporations and foundations and so forth, Shanahan came up with the idea that we ought to create an educational foundation as an adjunct to the chapter.
And that overlapping directorate
so that it would be a separate entity, but it would be controlled by the chapter and reflect chapter policy.
And so three of us were signatories to the creation of the corporation, which then incorporated.
It is an incorporation, as I understand it.
Prior to that time, a name that you and John and John Cunningham, from then the director of planning in El Paso, who had been very active on this,
short course task force and had been chairman of the short course task force for a couple of years were the, were the incorporators.
The three were required under state law to sign the articles of incorporation.
The articles of incorporation and the bylaws were prepared by a short course of an educational foundation task force, which I volunteered to head.
I told John that was the one thing I was really interested in doing.
somewhere around 1975 that the work started, and then it culminated in 76.
So that was the actual year of incorporation.
And the article of incorporation, I guess you'd call them, which is equivalent to the constitution of the body, remained intact.
There'd been no changes in that.
The bylaws had changed slightly and so forth.
but the overlapping terms and the ex-officio offices which linked the educational foundation, indeed a separate corporate body, but linked to the chapter, which itself is incorporated.
And part of the idea of incorporating influenced the chapter, but the foundation was separate.
Why was it separate?
Well, it was separate for one reason.
The chapter's purposes included lobbying,
And the foundations exclude lobbying in purely research, educational, and maybe moscenary purposes.
It was put in a different tax category from an IRS point of view.
And that was the reasoning behind it.
Yeah, we wanted to make sure we weren't going to be done by IRS.
Yes.
And we invited you and John and John Cunningham to be the incorporators because of your key roles
process of the short course.
And the main thing that the foundation was charged with doing, and we might insert in here somewhere, are there the articles of incorporation in the bylaws?
I don't know if the purposes are cited there, or at least extracts from them would be appropriate at this point.
Yeah.
That would be in the appendix.
Yeah.
The short course was definitely the key thing that they're supposed to do, but all other forms of help to the educational
activities related to planning in the state, both for lay planners and professional planners, were included as part of the legitimate purpose of the foundation.
So with that, I'd ask you what else you'd like me to talk about.
A quick summary of activity at the Council of Governments.
I was instrumental in the formation of the initial COG and helped to
developed some of the things that are not planning, per se, but which became part of the earmuffs of that cog.
And that was the initial annual retreats that were established there.
Some of the annual work programs that were developed there I had great inputs to.
And some of the things that I personally developed are still a part of that, the idea of rank ordering all the cities within the region and that kind of thing, the idea of comparing
size of the COG with the rest of the country and other states.
In fact, North Central Texas section now has compared its membership with several other state chapters and that kind of thing.
It's part of the, I must say, the Texas syndrome of bigger and better boosterism kind of thing.
Well, you've got quite a role to play in the 1970 census data book for that North Central Texas COG.
Personally,
I didn't have so much that people around my staff did.
A lot of times, inappropriately, I think that I may have gotten credit for some things that really people who worked for me were doing.
And indeed, there was a data book that was developed by COG from the 1970 census and a very important contribution.
And again, it used the computer technology to develop all these things and then was replicated in 1980 by COG
and his two urban studies at UT Arlington, once again, the same kind of thing.

And eventually, the number of people qualified in computer technology that came onto the staff to do the transportation planning and to develop the various models for projecting population and land use became very sophisticated and much beyond my own capabilities and experience.
But as far as the data management thing, in fact, I might add that

When in Tulsa, with the Metropolitan Data Center project, those of us who were involved became some of the initial, I shouldn't say initial founders, but some of the founders of the group known as URISA, the Urban and Regional Information Systems Association, which now is probably the preeminent body of its type for city and state and county and so forth.
The brothers at Osborne were involved in that, weren't they?
Osgood.
Osgood.
Osgood were on, both of those were on the staff, and they joined us shortly after.
in the late 50s, as I recall, Don Osgood, the elder, becoming eventually the director following my stint there in Tulsa.
And the other one, the younger one, he eventually moved to Texas and was the head of the North Central Texas section of the APA.
He has since moved back to Tulsa, as I recall, and they may be in partnership again.
But he had gone on to...
to Georgia Tech, got his master's degree on some facet of airport planning and he'd been working with
